headline: blizzard warning in effect
description:
Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow will continue into the weekend.

A long period of strong west winds gusting up to 70 km/h will produce poor visibility in blowing snow over the Amundsen Gulf and near the coastal communities.

###

Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility.

Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

headline: rainfall warning in effect
description:
Rain, heavy at times continues. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall.

What:
Rainfall amounts approaching 50 mm.

When:
This evening.

Where:
Northern sections of Metro Vancouver and the western Fraser Valley

Additional information:
A low pressure system approaching Metro Vancouver will bring rain tonight. The rain will taper off this evening.

Up to 50 mm of rain is forecast, and when combined with areas of frozen or partially frozen ground, runoff may cause localised flooding and water pooling on roads.

###

Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

headline: blowing snow advisory in effect
description:
Poor visibility locally near zero in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring.

Falling snow combined with southeast winds up to 40 gusting 60 km/h are producing areas of near zero visibility in blowing snow.

Conditions will begin to improve overnight into Saturday morning from west to east.

###

Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero.

Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

headline: marine weather statement in effect
description:
Risk of snow squalls and waterspouts. 
Arctic outflow winds along the mainland coast.

When:
Developing across BC coastal waters tonight and lasting into the weekend.

Remarks:
A cold and unstable airmass is over BC coastal waters and will reside offshore through much of the weekend. The cold airmass will lead to conditions favourable for the development of snow squalls and a risk of waterspouts.

An arctic ridge of high pressure will build across the BC Interior through the weekend. Gale force arctic outflow winds exiting many mainland inlets can also be expected. These outflow winds will develop by Saturday morning over the north coast and spread southwards along the coast through the weekend.

Conditions appear to stabilize somewhat beginning over northern offshore waters later in the day on Sunday and should begin to limit snowsquall activity and the risk of waterspout development.

###

headline: special weather statement in effect
description:
Convective flurries with a potential for snow squalls. 

When: Now to Sunday morning. 

Where: North Vancouver Island, Central Coast - coastal sections, and Haida Gwaii.

Additional information: A cold unstable airmass is spreading from Haida Gwaii to the south coast tonight. Conditions will become favourable for scattered flurries and a risk of snow squalls. On Saturday, another low pressure centre is developing near the central coast, enhancing the chance of snow squalls. The low pressure centre is moving to the south coast on Sunday, giving Haida Gwaii and the central coast a drying trend. 

A snow squall is a short period of moderate or heavy snowfall with strong gusty winds, causing a sharp reduction in visibility. Roads may be slippery and visibility may be poor in the snow.

###

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

headline: snowfall warning in effect
description:
Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected.

Snowfall with amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected.

Time span: Beginning Saturday evening in Saskatchewan and spreading into Manitoba overnight. The snow will ease from west to east through the day on Sunday.

Remarks: A low pressure system crossing southern Saskatchewan will bring widespread snow to the eastern Prairies. This will include an area of 10 to 15 centimetres of snow that will fall through portions of eastern Saskatchewan on Saturday evening and central Manitoba on Sunday.

The snow will ease to lingering flurries through Sunday into Monday.

###

Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

headline: special weather statement in effect
description:
Snow, blowing snow and Arctic outflow conditions

Where: Vancouver Island and Southern Gulf Islands, Sunshine Coast, Howe Sound, Whistler, Metro Vancouver, Fraser Valley.

When: Now into next week. 

Remarks: A wintry mix of weather conditions is expected to impact the South Coast of BC over the next several days. 

This weekend:
Heavy flurries and cold temperatures are expected this weekend as arctic air invades the region and an upper low brings the moisture. Be advised for sudden reduction in visibility in convective flurries if travelling around the South Coast. Accumulations are uncertain at this time as it will depend where the flurries develop but accumulating snow is likely in many areas this weekend. Warnings will be issued as necessary.

Next week:
Very cold and dry air is expected over the South Coast with outflow conditions from an arctic ridge of high pressure settling over the region. Temperatures will be 5 to 8 degrees Celsius below seasonal. Blowing snow is possible through the Fraser Valley with recent snowfall. Watch for accumulating snow over southern Vancouver Island from Qualicum Beach to the Saanich Peninsula early next week. Strong outflow winds will result in cold wind chills.

###

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

headline: arctic outflow warning in effect
description:
Very strong outflow winds and severely cold wind chill values are expected or occurring.

When: this evening until Tuesday, possibly continuing into Wednesday. 

Where: BC's North and Central coasts, including inland regions.

Additional information: An arctic airmass combined with very strong outflow winds will give low wind chill values near minus 20 to 25 from tonight to Tuesday, and possibly also on Wednesday. Temperatures will be the coldest in the overnight and early morning hours, but the strong, gusty winds will maintain the low windchills throughout the daytimes as well. Winds will be very strong through the mainland inlets, where northeasterly winds may gust up to 90 to 110 km/h beginning tonight.

###

Frostbite and hypothermia can occur within minutes if adequate precautions are not taken when outdoors. Any skin exposure is likely to result in frostbite. High winds may result in power outages and fallen tree branches.

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

headline: special weather statement in effect
description:
Snow, blowing snow and Arctic outflow conditions

Where: Vancouver Island and Southern Gulf Islands, Sunshine Coast, Howe Sound, Whistler, Metro Vancouver, Fraser Valley.

When: Now into next week. 

Remarks: A wintry mix of weather conditions is expected to impact the South Coast of BC over the next several days. 

This weekend:
Heavy flurries and cold temperatures are expected this weekend as arctic air invades the region and an upper low brings the moisture. Be advised for sudden reduction in visibility in convective flurries if travelling around the South Coast. Accumulations are uncertain at this time as it will depend where the flurries develop but accumulating snow is likely in many areas this weekend. Snowfall warnings have been issued for regions with heavier snowfall.

Next week:
Very cold and dry air is expected over the South Coast with outflow conditions from an arctic ridge of high pressure settling over the region. Temperatures will be 5 to 8 degrees Celsius below seasonal. Blowing snow is possible through the Fraser Valley with recent snowfall. Watch for accumulating snow over eastern Vancouver Island from Qualicum Beach to the Saanich Peninsula early next week. Strong outflow winds will result in cold wind chills.

###

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
